description: 1832; alteration (influenced by chipping squirrel) of earlier chitmunk, from older Ojibwe ačitamo˙nˀ (“squirrels”) (modern ajidamoo), literally ‘those who descend headlong’, from ačit- (“headfirst, face-down”) (compare modern ajijibizo (“he falls headfirst”), ajidagoojin (“he hangs upside down”)). The English verb developed due to the high-pitched voices of the American puppet and cartoon chipmunks in the group Alvin and the Chipmunks, who later starred in a popular children's TV show in the 1980s.

entries.meaning: A squirrel-like rodent of the genus Tamias, native mainly to North America.

verbs.description: chipmunk (third-person singular simple present chipmunks, present participle chipmunking, simple past and past participle chipmunked)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To speed up (an audio recording, especially a song), to make the voices high-pitched.
examples: The Dipset capo favors breezy, bass-heavy beats instead of chipmunked soul samples to celebrate the 'hood's favorite season.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To fill (one's mouth or cheeks) with food.
examples: Less than a minute to go and she's chewing almost viciously, her stuffed cheeks all chipmunked out like Dizzy Gillespie's in midsolo.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To stuff (food) into one's mouth or cheeks, sometimes as part of competitive eating.
examples: She chipmunked her breakfast into a porcelain cheek.
